      "title": "Charles' Law Experiment",
      "image": "https://www.thoughtco.com/thmb/6MsMmUK27akFhb8i89kj95J5iko=/1500x0/filters:no_upscale():max_bytes(150000):strip_icc()/GettyImages-545286316-433dd345105e4c6ebe4cdd8d2317fdaa.jpg",
      "description": "The Charles's Law experiment demonstrates that the volume of a gas is directly proportional to its absolute temperature at constant pressure. Procedure: 1. A narrow capillary tube sealed at one end is partially filled with a colored liquid, trapping a column of gas.\n2. The tube is immersed in a water bath, starting with ice water to lower the temperature.\n3. The length of the gas column (L, proportional to volume) is measured at various temperatures as the water bath is gradually heated.\n4. The temperature is recorded in Kelvin, and the corresponding gas column length is noted.\n\nObservation:\nA graph of gas column length (L) versus temperature (T) produces a straight line, confirming V ∝ T.\n\nConclusion:\nThe experiment verifies Charles's Law and shows that volume increases linearly with temperature at constant pressure.",
      "requirements": [
        "Rubber tubing",
        "Thermometer",
        "Beaker with water",
        "Source of heat (e.g., Bunsen burner or hot plate)",
        "Graph paper or plotting software"
      ],
      "duration": "6 min 30 secs",
      "difficulty": "Intermediate",
      "instructor": "Mr. John Mwangi",
      "rating": 4.9,
      "videoLink": "https://youtu.be/6hC2SHUWc0M"
    },
